40|$|Phase {{diagrams}} of two component mixtures are presented. One {{component is}} chosen from a homologous series of 4 -cyanobiphenyl 4 '-alkylbiphenyl- 4 -carboxylates (nCBB) {{in such a}} way that it possesses <b>a</b> nematic and <b>smectic</b> <b>A</b> 1 <b>phase</b> (i. e. n= 4, 5, 6, 7), and the second from a homologous series of 4 -alkyl- 4 '-cyanobiphenyls (nCB, n = 0 - 8). In nCBB-nCB system a strong enhancement of the <b>smectic</b> <b>Ad</b> <b>phase</b> is observed for the smectic member of nCB (n= 8) and the <b>smectic</b> <b>Ad</b> <b>phase</b> induction for the nematic members of nCB (n= 0 - 7). In most cases the temperature-composition area of the induced <b>smectic</b> <b>Ad</b> <b>phase</b> is <b>an</b> “island” surrounded by the nematic phase. The size and shape of the induced <b>smectic</b> <b>Ad</b> <b>phase</b> area depend on the alkyl chain length of both components. The smectic layer spacing is close to the dimer length of nCBB molecules, and slightly expands with increasing temperature and concentration of nCB. Exchange of a component with the unbranched alkyl chain with branched one favors induction of <b>Ad</b> <b>phase...</b>|$|R
40|$|Addition {{reaction}} of mesomorphic malonate-based dendrimers (up {{to the fourth}} generation) with C 60 gave liquid-crystalline fullerene derivatives. The cyanobiphenyl unit was used as liquid-crystalline promoter. The malonates presented nematic and/or <b>smectic</b> <b>A</b> <b>phases.</b> The fullerenes showed only <b>smectic</b> <b>A</b> <b>phases,</b> {{with the exception of}} the second generation dendrimer for which <b>smectic</b> <b>A</b> and nematic <b>phases</b> were observed. The supramolecular organization of the fullerene-based molecular units within the <b>smectic</b> <b>A</b> layers was investigated by X-ray diffraction. Two structural regimes were determined. For the low generation dendrimers, the supramolecular organization is determined by steric factors. For the high generation dendrimers, the mesogenic groups impose a microphase organization: due to lateral extension of the branching part of the molecule, the cyanobiphenyl groups arrange in a parallel fashion as in classical <b>smectic</b> <b>A</b> <b>phases,</b> the rest of the macromolecule being located between the mesogenic sublayers...|$|R
